# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: switched-capacitor-filter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/correlated-double-sampling] This is commonly used in switched-capacitor operational amplifiers to effectively double the gain of the charge sharing opamp, while adding an extra phase.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] An **LC circuit**, also called a **resonant circuit**, **tank circuit**, or **tuned circuit**, is an electric circuit consisting of an inductor, represented by the letter L, and a capacitor, represented by the letter C, connected together.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The circuit can act as an electrical resonator, an electrical analogue of a tuning fork, storing energy oscillating at the circuit's resonant frequency.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] LC circuits are used either for generating signals at a particular frequency, or picking out a signal at a particular frequency from a more complex signal; this function is called a bandpass filter.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] They are key components in many electronic devices, particularly radio equipment, used in circuits such as oscillators, filters, tuners and frequency mixers.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] An LC circuit is an idealized model since it assumes there is no dissipation of energy due to resistance.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Any practical implementation of an LC circuit will always include loss resulting from small but non-zero resistance within the components and connecting wires.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The purpose of an LC circuit is usually to oscillate with minimal damping, so the resistance is made as low as possible.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] While no practical circuit is without losses, it is nonetheless instructive to study this ideal form of the circuit to gain understanding and physical intuition.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] For a circuit model incorporating resistance, see RLC circuit.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The two-element LC circuit described above is the simplest type of **inductor-capacitor network** (or **LC network**).
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] It is also referred to as a *second order LC circuit* to distinguish it from more complicated (higher order) LC networks with more inductors and capacitors.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Such LC networks with more than two reactances may have more than one resonant frequency.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The order of the network is the order of the rational function describing the network in the complex frequency variable s.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Generally, the order is equal to the number of L and C elements in the circuit and in any event cannot exceed this number.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] An LC circuit, oscillating at its natural resonant frequency, can store electrical energy.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] A capacitor stores energy in the electric field (E) between its plates, depending on the voltage across it, and an inductor stores energy in its magnetic field (B), depending on the current through it.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] If an inductor is connected across a charged capacitor, the voltage across the capacitor will drive a current through the inductor, building up a magnetic field around it.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The voltage across the capacitor falls to zero as the charge is used up by the current flow.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] At this point, the energy stored in the coil's magnetic field induces a voltage across the coil, because inductors oppose changes in current.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] This induced voltage causes a current to begin to recharge the capacitor with a voltage of opposite polarity to its original charge.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Due to Faraday's law, the EMF which drives the current is caused by a decrease in the magnetic field, thus the energy required to charge the capacitor is extracted from the magnetic field.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] When the magnetic field is completely dissipated the current will stop and the charge will again be stored in the capacitor, with the opposite polarity as before.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Then the cycle will begin again, with the current flowing in the opposite direction through the inductor.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The charge flows back and forth between the plates of the capacitor, through the inductor.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The energy oscillates back and forth between the capacitor and the inductor until (if not replenished from an external circuit) internal resistance makes the oscillations die out.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The tuned circuit's action, known mathematically as a harmonic oscillator, is similar to a pendulum swinging back and forth, or water sloshing back and forth in a tank; for this reason the circuit is also called a *tank circuit*.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The natural frequency (that is, the frequency at which it will oscillate when isolated from any other system, as described above) is determined by the capacitance and inductance values.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] In most applications the tuned circuit is part of a larger circuit which applies alternating current to it, driving continuous oscillations.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] If the frequency of the applied current is the circuit's natural resonant frequency (natural frequency $f_{0}\,$ below), resonance will occur, and a small driving current can excite large amplitude oscillating voltages and currents.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] In typical tuned circuits in electronic equipment the oscillations are very fast, from thousands to billions of times per second.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Resonance occurs when an LC circuit is driven from an external source at an angular frequency *ω*0 at which the inductive and capacitive reactances are equal in magnitude.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The frequency at which this equality holds for the particular circuit is called the resonant frequency.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] where L is the inductance in henries, and C is the capacitance in farads.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The angular frequency *ω*0 has units of radians per second.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The resonance effect of the LC circuit has many important applications in signal processing and communications systems.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] and can be solved for A and B by considering the initial conditions.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Since the exponential is complex, the solution represents a sinusoidal alternating current.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Since the electric current I is a physical quantity, it must be real-valued.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Next, we can use Euler's formula to obtain a real sinusoid with amplitude *I*0, angular frequency *ω*0 = ⁠1/√*LC*⁠, and phase angle $\phi$ .
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] In the series configuration of the LC circuit, the inductor (L) and capacitor (C) are connected in series, as shown here.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The total voltage V across the open terminals is simply the sum of the voltage across the inductor and the voltage across the capacitor.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The current I into the positive terminal of the circuit is equal to the current through both the capacitor and the inductor.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Inductive reactance $\ X_{\mathsf {L}}=\omega L\$ increases as frequency increases, while capacitive reactance $\ X_{\mathsf {C}}={\frac {1}{\ \omega C\ }}\$ decreases with increase in frequency (defined here as a positive number).
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] At one particular frequency, these two reactances are equal and the voltages across them are equal and opposite in sign; that frequency is called the resonant frequency *f*0 for the given circuit.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] which is defined as the resonant angular frequency of the circuit.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] In a series configuration, XC and XL cancel each other out.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] In real, rather than idealised, components, the current is opposed, mostly by the resistance of the coil windings.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Thus, the current supplied to a series resonant circuit is maximal at resonance.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] In the series configuration, resonance occurs when the complex electrical impedance of the circuit approaches zero.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] First consider the impedance of the series LC circuit.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] where $\,\omega _{0}L\ \,$ gives the reactance of the inductor at resonance.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The numerator implies that in the limit as *ω* → ±*ω*0 , the total impedance Z will be zero and otherwise non-zero.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Therefore the series LC circuit, when connected in series with a load, will act as a band-pass filter having zero impedance at the resonant frequency of the LC circuit.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] When the inductor (L) and capacitor (C) are connected in parallel as shown here, the voltage V across the open terminals is equal to both the voltage across the inductor and the voltage across the capacitor.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] When XL equals XC, the two branch currents are equal and opposite.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] They cancel each other out to give minimal current in the main line (in principle, for a finite voltage V, there is zero current).
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Since total current in the main line is minimal, in this state the total impedance is maximal.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] There is also a larger current circulating in the loop formed by the capacitor and inductor.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] For a finite voltage V, this circulating current is finite, with value given by the respective voltage-current relationships of the capacitor and inductor.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] However, for a finite total current I in the main line, in principle, the circulating current would be infinite.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] In reality, the circulating current in this case is limited by resistance in the circuit, particularly resistance in the inductor windings.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Any branch current is not minimal at resonance, but each is given separately by dividing source voltage (V) by reactance (Z).
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Hence *I* = *⁠ V /Z⁠* , as per Ohm's law.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The same analysis may be applied to the parallel LC circuit.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] but for all other values of ω the impedance is finite.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Thus, the parallel LC circuit connected in series with a load will act as band-stop filter having infinite impedance at the resonant frequency of the LC circuit, while the parallel LC circuit connected in parallel with a load will act as band-pass filter.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The LC circuit can be solved using the Laplace transform.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The Laplace transform has turned our differential equation into an algebraic equation.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Solving for V in the s domain (frequency domain) is much simpler viz.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The final term is dependent on the exact form of the input voltage.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Two common cases are the Heaviside step function and a sine wave.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] where U is the amplitude and $\omega _{f}$ the frequency of the applied function.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The first evidence that a capacitor and inductor could produce electrical oscillations was discovered in 1826 by French scientist Felix Savary.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] He found that when a Leyden jar was discharged through a wire wound around an iron needle, sometimes the needle was left magnetized in one direction and sometimes in the opposite direction.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] He correctly deduced that this was caused by a damped oscillating discharge current in the wire, which reversed the magnetization of the needle back and forth until it was too small to have an effect, leaving the needle magnetized in a random direction.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] American physicist Joseph Henry repeated Savary's experiment in 1842 and came to the same conclusion, apparently independently.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Irish scientist William Thomson (Lord Kelvin) in 1853 showed mathematically that the discharge of a Leyden jar through an inductance should be oscillatory, and derived its resonant frequency.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] British radio researcher Oliver Lodge, by discharging a large battery of Leyden jars through a long wire, created a tuned circuit with its resonant frequency in the audio range, which produced a musical tone from the spark when it was discharged.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] In 1857, German physicist Berend Wilhelm Feddersen photographed the spark produced by a resonant Leyden jar circuit in a rotating mirror, providing visible evidence of the oscillations.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] In 1868, Scottish physicist James Clerk Maxwell calculated the effect of applying an alternating current to a circuit with inductance and capacitance, showing that the response is maximum at the resonant frequency.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The first example of an electrical resonance curve was published in 1887 by German physicist Heinrich Hertz in his pioneering paper on the discovery of radio waves, showing the length of spark obtainable from his spark-gap LC resonator detectors as a function of frequency.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] One of the first demonstrations of resonance between tuned circuits was Lodge's "syntonic jars" experiment around 1889.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] He placed two resonant circuits next to each other, each consisting of a Leyden jar connected to an adjustable one-turn coil with a spark gap.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] When a high voltage from an induction coil was applied to one tuned circuit, creating sparks and thus oscillating currents, sparks were excited in the other tuned circuit only when the circuits were adjusted to resonance.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] Lodge and some English scientists preferred the term "*syntony*" for this effect, but the term "*resonance*" eventually stuck.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The first practical use for LC circuits was in the 1890s in spark-gap radio transmitters to allow the receiver and transmitter to be tuned to the same frequency.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/lc-circuit] The first patent for a radio system that allowed tuning was filed by Lodge in 1897, although the first practical systems were invented in 1900 by Italian radio pioneer Guglielmo Marconi.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] A **switched capacitor** (**SC**) is an electronic circuit that implements a function by moving charges into and out of capacitors when electronic switches are opened and closed.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] Usually, non-overlapping clock signals are used to control the switches, so that not all switches are closed simultaneously.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] Filters implemented with these elements are termed *switched-capacitor filters*, which depend only on the ratios between capacitances and the switching frequency, and not on precise resistors.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] This makes them much more suitable for use within integrated circuits, where accurately specified resistors and capacitors are not economical to construct, but accurate clocks and accurate *relative ratios* of capacitances are economical.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] SC circuits are typically implemented using metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology, with MOS capacitors and MOS field-effect transistor (MOSFET) switches, and they are commonly fabricated using the complementary MOS (CMOS) process.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] Common applications of MOS SC circuits include mixed-signal integrated circuits, digital-to-analog converter (DAC) chips, analog-to-digital converter (ADC) chips, pulse-code modulation (PCM) codec-filters, and PCM digital telephony.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] The simplest switched-capacitor (SC) circuit is made of one capacitor $C_{S}$ and two switches **S1** and **S2** which alternatively connect the capacitor to either **in** or **out** at a switching frequency of f .
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] assuming $V_{\text{in}}$ is an ideal voltage source.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] When **S2** is closed (**S1** is open - they are never both closed at the same time), some of that charge is transferred out of the capacitor.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] Exactly how much charge gets transferred can't be determined without knowing what load is attached to the output.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] This charge is transferred at a rate of f .
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] This circuit is called a *parallel resistor simulation* because **in** and **out** are connected in parallel and not directly coupled.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] Other types of SC simulated resistor circuits are *bilinear resistor simulation*, *series resistor simulation*, *series-parallel resistor simulation*, and *parasitic-insensitive resistor simulation*.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] Charge is transferred from **in** to **out** as discrete pulses, not continuously.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] This transfer approximates the equivalent continuous transfer of charge of a resistor when the switching frequency is sufficiently higher (≥100x) than the bandlimit of the input signal.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] The SC circuit modeled here using ideal switches with zero resistance does not suffer from the ohmic heating energy loss of a regular resistor, and so ideally could be called a loss free resistor.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] However real switches have some small resistance in their channel or p–n junctions, so power is still dissipated.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] The capacitors are not ideal either and dissipate power as well.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] Because the resistance inside electric switches is typically much smaller than the resistances in circuits relying on regular resistors, SC circuits can have substantially lower Johnson–Nyquist noise.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] However, harmonics of the switching frequency may be manifested as high frequency noise that may need to be attenuated with a low-pass filter.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] SC simulated resistors also have the benefit that their equivalent resistance can be adjusted by changing the switching frequency (i.e., it is a programmable resistance) with a resolution limited by the resolution of the switching period.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] Thus *online* or *runtime* adjustment can be done by controlling the oscillation of the switches (e.g. using an configurable clock output signal from a microcontroller).
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] SC simulated resistors are used as a replacement for real resistors in integrated circuits because it is easier to fabricate reliably with a wide range of values and can take up much less silicon area.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] This same circuit can be used in discrete time systems (such as ADCs) as a sample and hold circuit.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] During the appropriate clock phase, the capacitor samples the analog voltage through switch **S1** and in the second phase presents this held sampled value through switch **S2** to an electronic circuit for processing.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] Electronic filters consisting of resistors and capacitors can have their resistors replaced with equivalent switched-capacitor simulated resistors, allowing the filter to be manufactured using only switches and capacitors without relying on real resistors.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] Switched-capacitor simulated resistors can replace the input resistor in an op amp integrator to provide accurate voltage gain and integration.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] One of the earliest of these circuits is the parasitic-sensitive integrator developed by the Czech engineer Bedrich Hosticka.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] This last equation represents what is going on in $C_{fb}$ - it increases (or decreases) its voltage each cycle according to the charge that is being "pumped" from $C_{s}$ (due to the op-amp).
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] However, there is a more elegant way to formulate this fact if T is very short.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] This switched-capacitor circuit is called "parasitic-sensitive" because its behavior is significantly affected by parasitic capacitances, which will cause errors when parasitic capacitances can't be controlled.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] "Parasitic insensitive" circuits try to overcome this.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] The delaying parasitic insensitive integrator has a wide use in discrete time electronic circuits such as biquad filters, anti-alias structures, and delta-sigma data converters.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] One useful characteristic of switched-capacitor circuits is that they can be used to perform many circuit tasks at the same time, which is difficult with non-discrete time components (i.e. analog electronics).
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] The multiplying digital to analog converter (MDAC) is an example as it can take an analog input, add a digital value d to it, and multiply this by some factor based on the capacitor ratios.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] The MDAC is a common component in modern pipeline analog to digital converters as well as other precision analog electronics and was first created in the form above by Stephen Lewis and others at Bell Laboratories.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] Switched-capacitor circuits are analysed by writing down charge conservation equations, as in this article, and solving them with a computer algebra tool.
[src:switched-capacitor-filter/switched-capacitor] For hand analysis and for getting more insight into the circuits, it is also possible to do a Signal-flow graph analysis, with a method that is very similar for switched-capacitor and continuous-time circuits.
